[[Field Marshal]] '''William Gustavus Nicholson, 1st Baron Nicholson''', [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath|GCB]] (2 March 1845 &ndash; 13 September 1918), was a [[British Army]] officer who served in the [[Second Anglo-Afghan War]], the [[Mahdist War]], the [[Third Anglo-Burmese War]], the [[Second Boer War]] and [[World War I]]. He became [[Chief of the General Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Imperial General Staff]] and was closely involved in the reorganization of the British Army in the early years of the 20th Century.

==Early life==
Born the youngest son of William Nicholson Nicholson (who had been born with the surname of Phillips but in 1827 assumed his mother's surname of Nicholson) and Martha Nicholson (n<U+00E9>e Rhodes),<ref name=odnb>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/35232|title=William Nicholson, 1st Baron Nicholson|publisher=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|accessdate=18 February 2012}}</ref> Nicholson graduated from [[Leeds Grammar School]] in 1863 and entered the [[Royal Military Academy, Woolwich]], where he was awarded the [[Pollock Medal]] the following year.<ref name=heath>Heathcote, p.228</ref>

==Military career==
Nicholson was commissioned as a lieutenant in the [[Royal Engineers]] on 21 March 1865.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=22950|supp=|startpage=1619|date=21 March 1865|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> From 1868 to 1871 he was employed on coastal fortification work in [[Barbados]], [[West Indies]].<ref name=heath/> Following this he was posted to [[India]], with the Public Works Department at [[Hyderabad, Pakistan|Hyderabad]], the [[Punjab (British India)|Punjab]] Irrigation Branch, and at [[Rawalpindi]] and [[Peshawar]] on barrack work and the construction of Army waterworks.<ref name=odnb/> 

Nicholson was promoted to the rank of [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 16 March 1878,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=24570|supp=|startpage=2451|date=9 April 1878|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> and posted to [[Afghanistan]], seeing service in the [[Second Anglo-Afghan War]].<ref name=heath/> He served in the first campaign as Field Engineer, [[Kandahar]] Field Force from 10 October 1878 to 5 March 1879, and as Royal Engineers Commander for the Thal-Chotiali Field Force from 6 March to 30 April 1879. During the second campaign of the war he served first as Field Engineer, 1st Division, [[Kabul Field Force]] from 23 September 1879 until 7 August 1880, being present at the action near Surkai Kotal on 14 October 1879, the defence of the Shutargardan in October 1879 and the defence of the [[Lataband]] in December 1879.<ref name=odnb/> He then served as Field Engineer, Kabul-Kandahar Field Force, taking part in the advance to the relief of [[Kandahar]], and being present at the [[battle of Kandahar]].<ref name=odnb/> During the Afghanistan campaigns, he was three times mentioned in despatches, was awarded a campaign medal with three clasps, and promoted to the brevet rank of major.<ref name=heath/>

He was appointed Secretary of the Defence Committee at [[Shimla|Simla]] in 1880 and was given the substantive rank of [[major]] on 1 March 1881.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=24944|supp=|startpage=977|date=1 March 1881|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> His time as secretary was interrupted by service in [[Egypt]] in 1882, where he served with the Indian contingent in the Egyptian Campaign.<ref name=heath/> His force made a successful flanking movement at the battle of Tel-el-Kebir<ref name=heath/> and opened up the way to [[Cairo]] by cutting the enemy<U+2019>s railway system near [[Zagazig]], where Nicholson, then with the cavalry, captured four trains under steam, which were later used to transport British infantry. His efforts earned him another campaign medal with clasp, the [[Order of Osmanieh]] (4th Class),<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=25169|supp=|startpage=5169|date=17 November 1882|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> and the Khedive's Star. He was promoted to the substantive rank of [[major]] on 21 March 1885.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=25454|supp=|startpage=1312|date=24 March 1885|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>

From 1885 he served as Assistant Adjutant General, [[Royal Engineers]] in [[Bengal]].<ref name=heath/> Service in the [[Third Anglo-Burmese War]], which stamped out the [[guerrilla warfare|guerrilla activities]] that followed the overthrow of King [[Thibaw Min]], earned Nicholson a further mention in despatches<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=25735|supp=|startpage=4758|date=2 September 1887|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> and promotion to the rank of brevet lieutenant colonel on 1 July 1887.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=25761|supp=|startpage=6376|date=25 November 1887|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>

Nicholson was appointed Military Secretary to [[Frederick Roberts, 1st Earl Roberts|Lord Roberts]], Commander-in-Chief in India on 1 July 1890<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=26114|supp=|startpage=6991|date=12 December 1890|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> and granted the substantive rank of [[colonel]] on 1 January 1891.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=26126|supp=|startpage=362|date=20 January 1891|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> He was appointed [[Order of the Bath|CB]] in the [[Queen's Birthday Honours]] 1891.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=26167|supp=|startpage=2922|date=30 May 1891|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> He was employed with the Military Works Department, India as a Chief Engineer from 1893 and was appointed Adjutant General for the [[Punjab (British India)|Punjab]] with rank of [[brigadier general]] in 1895.<ref name=heath/>
[[File:WilliamNicholsonBrompton01.jpg|thumb|right|225px|Funerary monument, Brompton Cemetery, London]]

Nicholson saw service on the North West Frontier of India as Chief of Staff for the [[Tirah Campaign]] in 1897 to 1898.<ref name=heath/> Lieutenant General [[William Lockhart (Indian Army officer)|Sir William Lockhart]] mentioned him in despatches referring to his "brilliant abilities" on 29 March 1898.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=26954|supp=|startpage=2180|date=5 April 1898|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> He was awarded a campaign medal with two clasps and advanced to [[Order of the Bath|KCB]] on 20 May 1898.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=26968|supp=|startpage=3165|date=20 May 1898|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> He was made [[Adjutant General]] in India on 24 February 1899 and promoted to the substantive rank of [[major-general]] for distinguished service in the field on 23 December 1899.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27306|supp=|startpage=2703|date=19 April 1901|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>

He was again appointed as Military Secretary to Lord Roberts, now Commander-in-Chief in [[South Africa]] on 23 December 1899 during the [[Second Boer War]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27146|supp=|startpage=8542|date=22 December 1899|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> He went on to be Director of Transport on 18 February 1900.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27203|supp=|startpage=3815|date=19 June 1900|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> While serving as a local major general,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27170|supp=|startpage=1436|date=2 March 1900|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> Nicholson was mentioned in Lord Roberts' despatch dated 31 March 1900: in this despatch Lord Roberts wrote, "...Colonel Sir W. Nicholson (local Major-Gen.), R.E., undertook, at my request, organisation of a transport department in the limited time available; he performed this duty with conspicuous ability."<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27282|supp=|startpage=845|date=8 February 1901|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> He was present at [[Battle of Paardeberg]] and at the actions at [[Poplar Grove]], [[Driefontein]], Vet and Zand Rivers, and in operations near [[Johannesburg]], [[Pretoria]] and Diamond Hill, and in the operations in the [[South African Republic|Transvaal]], east of Pretoria, during the latter half of 1900.<ref name=odnb/>

After the War, Nicholson returned to England where he was appointed Director-General of Mobilization and Military Intelligence at Headquarters on 1 May 1901<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27331|supp=|startpage=4573|date=9 July 1901|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> and promoted to lieutenant general on 4 November 1901.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27380|supp=|startpage=8090|date=26 November 1901|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>

Nicholson was made a Knight of Grace of the [[Venerable Order of Saint John]] on 5 March 1903<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27532|supp=|startpage=1503|date=6 March 1903|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> and made [[military attache|Chief Military Attach<U+00E9>]] to the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] in [[Manchuria]] in 1904 during the [[Russo-Japanese War]].<ref name=heath1>Heathcote, p.229</ref> He was appointed [[Quartermaster-General to the Forces]] and Member of the [[Army Council (1904)|Army Council]] on 18 December 1905<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27868|supp=|startpage=9320|date=29 December 1905|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> earning promotion to full [[general]] on 23 October 1906.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27960|supp=|startpage=7113|date=23 October 1906|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>

He was appointed as [[Chief of the General Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the General Staff]] on 2 April 1908,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28125|supp=|startpage=2567|date=3 April 1908|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> and, having been advanced to [[Order of the Bath|GCB]] in the [[Queen's Birthday Honours|King's Birthday Honours]] 1908,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28151|supp=yes|startpage=4641|date=23 June 1908|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> found his role re-designated [[Chief of the General Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Imperial General Staff]] ('CIGS') on 22 November 1909.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28311|supp=|startpage=8662|date=23 November 1909|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> He was appointed [[Aide-de-Camp General]] to [[George V|the King]] on 1 July 1910.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28391|supp=|startpage=4654|date=1 July 1910|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> In July 1910 he took part in the funeral procession following the death of [[Edward VII|King Edward VII]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28401|supp=yes|startpage=5481|date=26 July 1910|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>

As CIGS Nicholson was closely involved in the reorganization of the British Army, consolidating the Territorial Force and the creation of a modern general staff.<ref name=odnb/> He was promoted to [[field marshal]] on 19 June 1911,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28505|supp=yes|startpage=4597|date=16 June 1911|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>

Nicholson had a sharp tongue and one occasion [[John Arbuthnot Fisher|Admiral Fisher]] asked Maurice Hankey to stop <U+201C>Old Nick<U+201D> "stamping his hoof on his toes".<ref>Reid 2006, 167-70</ref>

At the [[Committee of Imperial Defence|CID]] meeting after the [[Agadir Crisis]] the [[First Sea Lord]] [[Arthur Wilson (Royal Navy officer)|Admiral Wilson]] said that in the event of war the Navy planned to land the Army on the Baltic Coast. Nicholson asked Wilson whether the Admiralty had maps of German strategic railways (to show how the Germans could rush reinforcements to invasion spots), and when Wilson said it was not the Admiralty<U+2019>s business to have such maps, Nicholson openly rebuked him and said that if the Navy <U+201C>meddled<U+201D> in military matters they needed not just to have such maps but to have studied them. Prime Minister [[H.H. Asquith]] ordered the Navy to fall in with the Army<U+2019>s plans to deploy an Expeditionary Force to France.<ref>Reid 2006, 167-70</ref>

Nicolson retired in March 1912 and was raised to the [[peerage]] as '''Baron Nicholson''', of [[Roundhay]] in the County of York on 4 October 1912.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28650|supp=|startpage=7292|date=4 October 1912|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>

From Autumn 1914, at the start of [[World War I]], he served on the [[Committee of Imperial Defence]], investigating the conduct of operations in [[Battle of Gallipoli|Gallipoli]] and [[Mesopotamian Campaign|Mesopotamia]] and in 1916 he was appointed to the [[Dardanelles Commission]].<ref name=heath1/>

Nicolson was also [[Colonel Commandant]], Royal Engineers from October 1916.<ref name=heath2>Heathcote, p.230</ref> His other duties included those of Chairman of the Territorial Forces Association for [[London]].<ref name=odnb/> Less than two months before [[Armistice Day]], Lord Nicholson died in his home at 15 Pont Street, London, aged 73.<ref name=odnb/> He left no heirs and the barony died with him.<ref name=heath2/> He was buried in [[Brompton Cemetery]], London.<ref name=odnb/>

==Family==
In 1871 he married Victorie d' Allier (n<U+00E9>e Dillon); they had no children.<ref name=odnb/>

==Decorations and campaign medals==
* Knight Grand Cross of the Most Honourable Order of the Bath (G.C.B.), 1908.
* Knight Commander of the Most Honourable Order of the Bath (K.C.B.), 1898.
* Companion of the Most Honourable Order of the Bath (C.B.), 1891.
* Afghanistan 1878<U+2013>1880 Medal with clasps [CHARASIA][KABUL][KANDAHAR].
* Egypt 1882 Medal with clasp [TEL-EL-KEBIR].
* India General Service Medal 1854 with clasp [BURMA 1883<U+2013>6].
* India General Service Medal 1895 with clasps [PUNJAB FRONTIER 1897<U+2013>98][TIRAH 1897<U+2013>98]
* Queen's South Africa Medal with 5 clasps
* Turkish Order of Osmanieh, 4th Class
* Khedive's Star
* Grand Cordon of the Order of the Rising Sun
* Japanese War Medal

